        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la" resp="#JP" source="https://www.zotero.org/groups/382445/items/FZWWPUD6">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>s</abbr><ex>acrum</ex></expan><g ref="#interpunct">·</g>
                    <lb n="2"/>Cassia <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> Galene
                    <lb n="3"/>vixit <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>ann</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <num value="40">XXXX</num>
                    <lb n="4" /><expan><abbr>C</abbr><ex>aius</ex></expan> Iulius <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> Macedo
                    <lb n="5"/>uxori <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> pissiimae
                    <lb n="6"/><g ref="#interpunct">·</g> fecit <g ref="#interpunct">·</g>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp><app><note>Text of Bivona and Ferrua (but with interpuncts formally recorded)</note></app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Sacred to the shades of the underworld. Cassia Galene lived 40 years. Caius Iulius Macedo made (this) for his most dutiful wife</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The piece's provenance is uncertain. Ferrua suggested that it should be from Palermo, but it is one of three which he so attributed without much evidence, as one of the three is from Taormina and one from Rome; there appears however to be no documentation regarding the origin of this piece, which Bivona therefore lists among the 'ignota'.</p>
            </div>
